Text:
RT @sociologysport : Unless there is consistent Disability representation in the legislative, executive, and judiciary: these problems will continue. My disability is political no matter what anyone says.
(@nuthetics) (8/8)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: RT @sociologysport : The problem also is the fragmentation that exists within the Disability community. A majority of voices are drowned out and select individuals are token inspiration porn. Is anyone listening to the grassroots? (@Shampa_Sengupta ) (7/8)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: RT @sociologysport : A Disability is a deterrent for what is otherwise an able bodied society. Whether in our educational institutions, homes, or public places. Instead of focusing on these issues we are bothered with what people are wearing. In 2022. (@NPRD_IN) (4/8)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: RT @sociologysport : The PWD Act 2016 is not implemented at all whether in public or private buildings in this country. This is because our Govts teach us to think of PWD as "divine". We're still stuck in the 1500s as far as diversity and Disability goes. (@Jussri) (3/8)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: RT @sociologysport : Love how this is being made a thing against one restaurant in Gurgaon. The problem is not isolated. As a person with a Disability not one single place in this country is disability friendly. From inaccessible infrastructure to loud over the top music and insensitive owners.(1/8) https://t.co/pWgQyunPON
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: RT @sociologysport : For owners of these private establishments, a person with a Disability is a deterrent to business. "Weirdos" who will scare "able-bodied" customers away. (@joshimanasi11)(2/8)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: I keep you all in my prayers, always. 🙏🏻 (12/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: I am throughly grateful to all the people esp the ones who were present on 2nd Dec 2011 on the busy streets of Mumbai. All of you who took out time on your way to work and college, to be there for a stranger.. to be around me and save my life. (11/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: and friends who have always believed in me and pushed me to be the best version of myself, my mentors and teammates who give me the best guidance and help me in my decision making. (10/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: My colleagues and friends have been extremely supportive. Thank you to my prosthetists, physios, trainers, and now coaches, without whom I could not have been here. My family, sponsors, employer, (9/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
the love from people around me and trust people have toward me is making me a responsible person standing up for myself and for others. 

I have deep gratitude toward the people who have touched my life after my amputation. (8/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: Pursuing sports is giving me a huge opportunity to share my views and experiences with the world and most importantly giving me opportunity to change lives of others. The appreciation from youngsters, (7/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: sometimes it doesn’t and I don’t shy away from taking a break too. I am doing what I love everyday and this physical labour of putting hours into my fitness is reaping benefits. (6/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
I own my disability and am not at all ashamed to ask for what is rightfully mine. It takes a toll sometimes to make others understand of my realities but the world is changing are people are becoming allies.

I push myself everyday. Sometimes my body allows, (5/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
I want to shout out loud and thank everyone on my socials and share personal pictures of my friends & family who have made sure I am where I am but the nature of social media is such that I am scared. 

Right now I am in a way better space physically and mentally. (4/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: I realised that I have so much to say that it can’t fit into this small space. (3/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
I am extremely grateful to be alive and to be doing my bit for self and for the people around me.

I really wanted to write a long post and share how I have felt over the years and then when I sat writing this, (2/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: It is 10 years today of my accident and subsequent living life as a person with a disability; an amputee. In these 10 years I have learnt so much and I would not have been here without the support of my doctors, nurses, my family, friends and colleagues. (1/12)
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
RT @PaulineCastres : You might get it wrong yes, because there's a lot of unlearning to do.

But remember disabled people do not just exist to educate others. 

Many of us do that in our free time and for free. Often with limited energy/time.

There are ways to learn using resources available.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
RT @PaulineCastres : Finally, support us.

Many of us cannot work or have faced such horrible experiences at work that we've ended up unemployed.

Buy our stuff. Give to the Patreon of a disabled maker/writer. Look up disabled makers you can support.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: RT @PaulineCastres : Make sure you explore intersectional aspects in the disability discourse - where disability interacts with other characteristics (gender, race, nationality, sexual orientation, etc.).
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
RT @PaulineCastres : Understand that disability & disabled people belong to all the spaces: transport, education, climate, work, healthcare, etc.

Ask yourself why is disability not central to those areas, but often siloed as a separate issue.

Ask yourself why segregation is still so often the norm.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
RT @PaulineCastres : Learn about our rights: the Equality Act in the UK, the ADA in the US, the UNCRPD (UN Convention), etc.

Learn that disability rights are human rights.

Learn what ableism is. Learn how common ableism is.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
RT @PaulineCastres : Using a wheelchair for a day doesn't make you an ally to the disability community.

So, what does?

Listening to and campaigning alongside disabled people.

Text:
I found calm, peace and balance when I was still learning new ways to understanding self.
This was 2013 and I've come a long way. 
Extremely thankful to my teachers who taught me self connection
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
Self Awareness & understanding of self is one of the most important thing that I learnt there. I followed the techniques taught and followed it when I was working in IT.
This self discipline has been very useful especially when I decided to pursue sports as a career later in 2016 https://t.co/hAXa9lm4uQ
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: I understood, if I can stay in a room following silence for 10days, doing meditation  following strict discipline for the period, sleep on thin bed/mat, meditate and follow time table from 4.30am to 9.30pm, live alone doing this, then I can do anything
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: By the end of 10 days, I was more secure, more understanding,  more sensitive, more self aware and more powerful as a person. I spent 10 days with myself going into a meditative state knowing how amazing we are as people. https://t.co/5qove8smcY
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
I stayed in this accommodation waking up at 3.30am and going for 1st mediation session at 4.30

Vipassana meditation was my 1st introduction to multiple mediation techniques that I have tried over the years https://t.co/O2hSpvsbSO
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: Pallavi ji is one of the person who has pushed me to be more independent and one of the reason how I won my 1st world's silver in 2015. https://t.co/CMcD6OvQl9
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: My yoga teacher, Pallavi Mishra had introduced me to the nuances of mediation and pushed me to pursue this line of mediation to know the power of self through spending more time with self https://t.co/OJtt9UlQrf
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: I did this course just 1.5 years into amputation where I was still learning navigating the world as a newly disabled person. I was not aware how strong or independent I was until this experience https://t.co/zKWWXkS8Dj
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: At first, I could not sit in meditation for more than 15 mins. Sitting in 1 position would affect my blood supply in my leg and I would get into a state where I could not feel my leg. It scared me.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
8 years ago I completed my first Vipassana meditation course in Igatpuri, Mah. It was a 10 day residential course where I had to stay in an ashram learning basics of mediation.
No communication, no phone, no talking, no books. Complete 10 days without speaking to anyone https://t.co/5qjvcnOkOi
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:

#ToScience #AssistiveDevicesForAll #innovation
#AssistiveTechnology
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
My teammates have got used to seeing it charge and use the socket to store mobile phone or water bottle or napkin/ towel for use.

The technology has helped me to lead an independent life and has enabled me to participate fully in community, work, and enjoy sports, music, art.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: Here in the picture is me charging my prosthetic leg in my academy because I forgot to charge it at home and got my charger to the academy to fully charge till I play on my sports prosthetic.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: In this lockdown I've charged it only when it emit sounds to let me know its time and many a times I've gone out on my crutches as my prosthetic is always out of charge.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: The battery lasts for a day or two, and no, it does not depend on use. If you use it or no, it still needs to be charged every 2 days.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
For me, the best feature was ability to switch between modes from walking to cycling to squatting and gave me a lot of independence .

The only thing I need to always remember is keeping it charged or else it goes into a fail safe mode.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: At that time it was one of the wonder of the world designed for an above knee amputee which helped in stumble recovery along with giving its user ability to stand for long time, walk on different surfaces, go down the stairs, ride bike, and many other functions.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: It is a microprocessor based knee with a stable foot which replicates a human gait pattern.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

nstead I need accessibility, change in attitude, low cost high end equipments and aids, equal opportunity in education and employment and healthcare.

Text:
Yesterday's Friends reunion episode made me go back 2 a time where I was watching episodes stuck 2 a hospital bed, with laptop on my lunch table. I realised how far I've reached frm that bed. 

I will always remember room no 108 & doctors, nurses, caretakers who bexame my Friends
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
When I couldn't even turn sides, watching Friends after my 2nd amputation. 
My college friends would stay over in hospital and would watch a few episodes with them and this memory is still intact.

Friends as a series helped me take my hospitalisation in a fun way \2
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
I watched friends series for the first time when I was in the hospital in 2012. With years of my friends asking me to watch, I finally picked it to binge watch during my free time in hospital. It kept me busy and away from unnecessary thoughts. 
There I was, laughing in my bed \1
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
Currently, my sibling and I, we have such time in hand to be able to dedicate our efforts towards booking an appointment.  But for those of you who can’t spare such time, here are our learnings
1.Use laptop instead of phone for bookings.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:

Remember, you are competing with 18+ tech savvy generation of India to book one slot for self .

Text: My siblings and myself, we had set up alerts on Telegram and Paytm to ensure that we don’t miss an opportunity. But in vain. One can literally see 100 slots being filled in a matter of few seconds.

Text: In regards to bookings, in Ahmedabad, at a time only 100 slots get added per centre and currently there are approx. 50-52 centres allocated for vaccination for 18+. The slots start getting added from 3.30 PM onwards at random intervals.

Text:
“Its going to be my year” is what I told myself at the start of 2020, and it indeed was! 
How was your 2020?
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: 17. Got listed as BBC 100 women/ Forbes 100 self-made women/ BBC Indian sportswoman of the year nomination/ Cosmo magazine spicy noodles list/ Multiple publications wrote about me and I helped change the narrative how people should write about people with disabilities
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
15. Speaking at various forums on how to deal with lockdown and shared my story with numerous people through virtual talks at corporates, schools, colleges, events
16. Honorary Rotary membership with Rotary Club of Deonar. Thank you club
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
11. Donated complete KBC winnings to Gopichand Academy
12. Time Next Generation Leaders and got featured on their Asia cover
13. Got myself a car and started driving long distance again
14. One of a Kind Barbie❤️
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
7. Learnt to workout at home/ train at home
8. Got myself a running prosthesis and re-learnt running.
9. Learnt cycling long distance – fell down quite a few times. It was like going back to school time.
10. Felt more empowered because of family support
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
3. Filed Intervention application in the Supreme Court with Nipun Malhotra for reducing/removing GST on assistive devices used by PwD.
4. Spent more time with family.
5. Attended online courses
6. Sponsored an above knee prosthesis for my friend's house help’s family.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
I would like to share them with you (in no particular order):
1. Fought/dealt with COVID-19 in family – most difficult 1.5 months
2.  Lost my Grandma in March (her birth month at 92) who also made sure we're home before lockdown
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
I also upped my skills be it speaking or badminton or re-learning how to run and cycle.

Few things that happened this year, helped me appreciate life (and my family) even more than before. Few things that I did / contributed to that made feel proud and happy about myself.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: I realised the power of story sharing and used it effectively to tell people how to deal with a loss, how to be an ally and how to manoeuvre a difficult time. This year I gave back to society in whatever way I could.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: Along with this, I also used my time to learn more about disability rights and how to use my voice for the betterment of the community.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
And just like that we reached the last day of this unusual yet eventful year. It has been a year of highs and lows - sharing with you all how the year has been for me.
This year I focussed more on 'Me' and my overall development.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: Please do not be harsh and critical to yourself when such things happen. How much ever care we take, we can never be ready for tragedies. Life sucks, sometimes we get hit by a truck and all we have to do is heal.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: Sometimes due to no fault of ours, we can be on the receiving end because someone else was not doing their job properly, whether it is driving, or ensuring working of traffic lights, or staying home because of covid symptoms or wearing a mask.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: But from my accident and COVID-19 experience, I realised that one person cannot bring about a change we desire, it is a combined effort.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: Even with Covid-19, since the pandemic announcement my family and myself have been following all safety protocols. I have made multiple videos to educate people around this.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: I was always very careful with my driving, would obey all laws, give way to pedestrians and travel by public transport like trains and buses to reduce my carbon foot print too.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
Where my parents have been my inspiration, my siblings are my constant cheerleaders.

We always hear of tragedies in people’s life and we think "it happens with other people, thats life", never realising that it can happen to us. Like accidents or covid.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: My friends and colleagues who encouraged me every minute and my organisation for being supportive. But wherever I am right now, would not have been possible without the hope, belief and trust by my family.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: I am grateful to my flatmates and building friends. But more than that, I am grateful to the doctors, nurses, and housekeeping staff at MGM hospital, Vashi, Mumbai who saved me and took care of me. I am thankful to the team of prosthetists who made me walk again.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
Sports and opportunities I have got through sports have changed my perspectives and given me new direction altogether. I never knew it would take me here where I am right now.
I am so grateful to my coaches, sports physios and trainers.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
Although I am proud of the decisions Ive made and the directions I’ve chosen, I still feel that the journey of last few years has been challenging.
I was privileged to choose sports and am proud of myself that I continued giving my 100% to it inspite of 10,000 obstacles.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: 9 years is such a long time if you think, but to me, even now if someone asks me to choose between a life that I was leading before accident and now, I’d still choose the pre-amputation life. The struggles I have faced and am facing still exists.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
When sports took this huge break globally, I got a lifetime worth of recognition in last 2 months.

But In all this now when I look back, I realise how far I have come from that 2nd Dec 2011 incident.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: October came with biggest recognition worldwide with Time Magazine Next Generation Leader and subsequent Asia Cover, then came Inclusion as Barbie Shero by Mattel Toys and now recently making it to BBC 100 Women of 2020 in November.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
…obsessively cleaning and following lockdown social media trends too. I also made the most of Covid Lockdown by re-lerning two skills - cycling and running.

To tell you the truth, I never knew what the year had in store for me.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: I spent this time telling and listening to finer stories of travel we all siblings had taken, playing card games, working out as a group, learning and reading, clicking pictures, capturing videos, attending online sessions, giving talks and interviews, doing gardening,…
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
Highlight before Covid Lockdown was, being nominated for BBC's Indian Sportswoman of the Year 2019, as the only para athlete among 4 other able bodied Indian sportswomen.
The Covid lockdown got my family under the same roof after 3 long years.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: At the start of 2020, I was nominated/ awarded ‘Para-Athlete of the Year’ by various media houses like Espn, Times of India, HT, to name a few.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: Last year on 3rd Dec I was recognised with a National Award as ‘Best Sports person with a disability’ and got an opportunity to meet the President of India.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: 2020 has been such a big year for me- from recognitions, to understanding finer things about life and relationships, to now my family fighting COVID-19.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
On 2nd Dec 2011, I met with an accident, ironically just one day before International day for Persons with Disabilities. 
Every year on this day, I take out time to reflect on the past year and how much life has changed.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: Today is 9 years of me meeting with an unfortunate road accident and surviving it.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: 2020 was MY year but still it never felt like it was mine.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

We all have isolated ourselves & are taking our medications. It is very different here as the city is celebrating Diwali & new year and there's shortage of people at hospital, in testing.. Etc.

If you've come in contact with our family, please look out for symptoms & get tested
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
Any idea why labs give you a Presumptive Positive tag?
My siblings have clear negative COVID-19 result and my parents have clear positive. It's just me who's got Presumptive Positive. https://t.co/be1zFvk6dX
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: As we celebrate new year today, our family is now managing this illness in a very unique way. We all are isolated from each other doing video calls and taking care.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
This Diwali was one of the craziest for us. My mother tested +ve of Covid 19 and had to be hospitalised. Yesterday we got subsequent testing done & today we got our test results which states that my father is +ve & I'm 'Presumptive Positive'.
My mother is stable & recovering now

Text: @sanatgoel You're very kind and empathetic to think that. There's always a priority for senior citizens, pregnant ladies and people with disabilities. If you do not wish to take it is upto you.
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text: @rg14276 Exactly right!
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
@sanatgoel Yeah, this is so wrong. People with locomotor disabilities are standing in long queues because people are not sensitive and they worry about what people think.
Thank you for your support
Name: Manasi G. Joshi

Text:
Just a reminder to all amputee folks out here, do not shy away from skipping long queues in this COVID times. Get your work done, go home quickly.
Do not think what people are going to say.
We have always been such rule followers, that we forget that skipping queue is a rule too
Name: Manasi G. Joshi
